<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900622-0055</DOCNO><DOCID>900622-0055.</DOCID><HL>   Grumman, Boeing   Settle Cost Dispute   On Defense Program</HL><DATE>06/22/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10</SO><CO>   GQ BA</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><LP>   BETHPAGE, N.Y. -- Grumman Corp. and Boeing Co. said theysettled their dispute over costs for the U.S. defense programcalled Joint Stars.   &quot;The settlement eliminates substantial claims by bothparties concerning responsibility for the costs of completionof the first two Joint Stars aircraft,&quot; the companies said. AGrumman spokesman said no details of the settlement would bereleased.</LP><TEXT>   In a joint statement, Grumman Chairman John O'Brien andBoeing Vice Chairman Malcolm Stamper said, &quot;This settlementwill improve our mutual concentration on other importantassignments on which we are working together.&quot;   In 1985, Grumman won a $657 million contract for afive-year development program for the Joint SurveillanceTarget Attack Radar System, which will identify groundtargets and guide aircraft and missiles. The value of thecontract has since been increased to $850 million, Grummansaid.   Meanwhile, Boeing won an $80.2 million subcontract tomodify two aircraft for the radar system's &quot;aerial platform,&quot;but late in 1987 Boeing requested a $122.5 million priceincrease. Boeing alleged that Grumman's demands on thesubcontractor had departed from the contract and driven upcosts.   For its part, Grumman then sought an undisclosed sum fromBoeing &quot;for damages caused by deficiencies in performance ofthe subcontract.&quot;   Grumman said Joint Stars is &quot;in the final phases&quot; offlight testing by Grumman, with a U.S. Air Force evaluationplanned for this year.</TEXT></DOC>